Can you swap your data source — REST to GraphQL, real API to a mock — without editing a single component? If not, your components depend on the wrong things. That’s what Dependency Inversion fixes.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Here’s a quick test for any React component you’ve written. Open it and ask: if the backend team migrated this endpoint from REST to GraphQL tomorrow, how many of my components would I have to edit?
If the honest answer is “a lot,” your UI is wired directly to a concrete data-fetching implementation. The chart doesn’t just display revenue — it knows the URL, the fetch library, and the response shape. That coupling is the problem the Dependency Inversion Principle solves, and it’s the principle that closes out this SOLID-for-frontend series.
The principle, stated plainly
There are two halves, and both matter:
High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules. Both should depend on abstractions.
Abstractions should not depend on details. Details should depend on abstractions.
The “high-level module” is your RevenueChart — it expresses business intent: show revenue over time. The "low-level module" is axios.get("/api/revenue") — a concrete detail about how data arrives. When the chart imports the fetcher directly, the high-level thing depends on the low-level thing. Dependency Inversion flips the arrow: both should depend on an abstraction — "something that gives me revenue data" — and the concrete fetcher should be plugged in from the outside.
The violation: a chart welded to its data source
// RevenueChart.jsx — knows far too much
import axios from "axios";
import { LineChart } from "./LineChart";function RevenueChart() {
const [data, setData] = useState([]); useEffect(() => {
axios
.get("https://api.acme.com/v2/revenue")
.then((res) => setData(res.data.points.map((p) => ({ x: p.date, y: p.amount_cents / 100 }))));
}, []); return <LineChart data={data} />;
}This component is doing three jobs and depending on all the wrong concretes:

• It depends on axios (a library), a specific URL (an environment detail), and a response shape (a backend contract).

• You cannot render it in Storybook without hitting a live server.

• You cannot unit-test it without mocking the network.

• Moving to GraphQL, or pointing staging at a different host, means editing this file — and every other component shaped like it.
The chart, a high-level concept, is chained to low-level details. Reusability is zero.
The refactor: depend on an abstraction, inject the detail
The abstraction is just a contract: “give me revenue points.” The component depends on that, not on how it’s fulfilled. There are two clean ways to inject the concrete implementation in React — props for local cases, context for app-wide ones.
Step 1 — define the abstraction (a plain function signature, or a TS type):
// the contract every data source must satisfy
type RevenuePoint = { x: string; y: number };
type RevenueSource = () => Promise<RevenuePoint[]>;Step 2 — the chart depends only on the abstraction, passed in:
// RevenueChart.jsx — now it knows nothing about axios, URLs, or response shapes
function RevenueChart({ loadRevenue }) {
const [data, setData] = useState([]);
useEffect(() => { loadRevenue().then(setData); }, [loadRevenue]);
return <LineChart data={data} />;
}Step 3 — the concrete detail lives at the edge, and gets plugged in:
// revenueSource.rest.js — one of possibly many implementations
import axios from "axios";export const restRevenueSource = async () => {
const res = await axios.get("/api/revenue");
return res.data.points.map((p) => ({ x: p.date, y: p.amount_cents / 100 }));
};<RevenueChart loadRevenue={restRevenueSource} />Swapping to GraphQL is now a new file, not an edit to the chart:
// revenueSource.graphql.js — satisfies the same RevenueSource contract
export const graphqlRevenueSource = async () => {
const { data } = await client.query({ query: REVENUE_QUERY });
return data.revenue.map((p) => ({ x: p.date, y: p.amount }));
};The chart never changes. The detail depends on the abstraction; the abstraction depends on nothing.
Scaling it up with Context as the injection point
Passing loadRevenue through props is perfect for one component. When many components across the tree need the same services, threading props gets noisy. React Context is the idiomatic dependency-injection container for the frontend — inject the implementation once at the root, consume the abstraction anywhere.
const DataContext = createContext(null);export function DataProvider({ source, children }) {
return <DataContext.Provider value={source}>{children}</DataContext.Provider>;
}export const useRevenue = () => useContext(DataContext).loadRevenue;// production root wires the real implementation
<DataProvider source={{ loadRevenue: restRevenueSource }}>
<Dashboard />
</DataProvider>// a test or Storybook wires a fake — same contract, no network
<DataProvider source={{ loadRevenue: async () => fixtureRevenue }}>
<RevenueChart />
</DataProvider>The components consume useRevenue() — an abstraction. Which concrete source backs it is a decision made entirely at the composition root.
The payoff
Inverting these dependencies unlocks things that are painful otherwise:

• Tests run offline and fast. Inject a fixture function; no fetch mocking, no network flakiness.

• Storybook works on every component, because every data source can be faked at the boundary.

• Backend migrations stop being UI projects. REST to GraphQL becomes a new source file, not a sweep through the component tree.

• Environments are configuration, not code edits. Staging, prod, and demo modes just inject different sources at the root.

• Decoupling compounds. Your chart is reusable across products that fetch revenue completely differently.
A grounding caveat: DIP is not “abstract everything.” A component that reads props.label doesn't need a LabelProvider. Invert the dependencies that change independently of the UI — data sources, analytics clients, feature flags, auth — and leave genuinely stable details concrete. The smell to chase is a component importing a service module directly; that's where the arrow needs flipping.
Closing the loop on SOLID
Dependency Inversion is where the series pays off as a whole. It builds directly on Interface Segregation — you can only inject a clean abstraction if that abstraction is lean and focused rather than a fat, do-everything interface. And it brings us back to where we started: keeping a component blind to how its data arrives is the deepest expression of the Single Responsibility Principle — the chart’s one job is to render, not to fetch. Run the five principles together and you get components that are testable, swappable, and safe to change. That’s the entire promise of SOLID, delivered on the frontend.
